      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to question the \"overwhelmingly\" part, as historians do debate the depth of the movement's success, but the consensus is that the legislative victories were the essential first step that made any real change possible. While critics argue the laws didn't immediately erase poverty or police brutality, these legal frameworks dismantled the constitutional basis for Jim Crow, creating the necessary platform for future civil rights advancements. Without this foundational shift in federal power and public morality, the systemic issues you mention would have remained entrenched and unaddressable for decades.",
      "source": "target",
